/*
====================================================================
üìò Lecture: Big-O Notation (Questions, Proofs & Deep Understanding)
(Analysis of Algorithms)
====================================================================

This lecture is the FINAL lecture on Big-O notation.
Previous lectures covered:
- Basic idea of asymptotic analysis
- Meaning of order
- Dominating term concept

In this lecture:
- We solve QUESTIONS
- We build INTUITION
- We derive CONCLUSIONS
- We understand what Big-O REALLY represents

‚ö†Ô∏è This lecture is NOT about memorizing formulas.
It is about understanding growth and comparison of functions.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Question 1
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Q. If the time taken by an algorithm is independent of input size,
   then what is its time complexity? How do we represent it?

--------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Understanding the Scenario
--------------------------------------------------------------------
If input size increases or decreases,
but execution time remains SAME,
then the algorithm takes CONSTANT TIME.

Example:
- Input size = 10    ‚Üí constant time
- Input size = 100   ‚Üí constant time
- Input size = 1000  ‚Üí constant time
- Input size = 10000 ‚Üí constant time

CPU speed may differ:
- 1 millisecond
- 1 microsecond
- 1 nanosecond

But the IMPORTANT point:
üëâ Time does NOT depend on input size.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Algorithm Example (Very Important)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Given a SORTED array A.

Algorithm:
return A[0];

Explanation:
- First element is always the smallest
- No loop
- No recursion
- Only ONE operation

No matter how large the array is,
execution time remains constant.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Representing Time as a Function
--------------------------------------------------------------------
We represent time as a function of input size n.

Since time is constant:
f(n) = 100

(100 is just an example; any constant works)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
5. Choosing g(n)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Constant time is represented using:
g(n) = 1

We want to prove:
f(n) = O(1)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Applying Big-O Definition
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Big-O definition:

f(n) ‚â§ c ¬∑ g(n)   for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ

Substitute values:
100 ‚â§ c ¬∑ 1
100 ‚â§ c

Choose:
c = 100
n‚ÇÄ = 1

Hence:
f(n) = O(1)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
7. Important Insight
--------------------------------------------------------------------
O(1) does NOT mean time = 1.

O(1) means:
Time is CONSTANT.

All of these belong to O(1):
- 5
- 10
- 100
- 1000
- 100000

--------------------------------------------------------------------
8. Big-O Represents a SET of Functions
--------------------------------------------------------------------
O(1) is NOT a single function.

It represents:
{5, 10, 50, 100, 1000, ...}

Any function independent of n belongs to O(1).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
9. Question 2
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Q. If f(n) = n¬≤ + n + 1 and g(n) = n¬≤,
   then what is the order of f(n)?

--------------------------------------------------------------------
10. Dominating Term Concept
--------------------------------------------------------------------
As n ‚Üí ‚àû:
- n¬≤ dominates n
- n¬≤ dominates constant

So:
n¬≤ + n + 1 behaves like n¬≤

--------------------------------------------------------------------
11. Formal Proof Using Big-O
--------------------------------------------------------------------
We want:
n¬≤ + n + 1 ‚â§ c ¬∑ n¬≤   for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ

Choose:
c = 2

Then:
n¬≤ + n + 1 ‚â§ 2n¬≤
n + 1 ‚â§ n¬≤

This holds for n ‚â• 2.

Hence:
f(n) = O(n¬≤)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
12. Question 3
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Q. If f(n) = 2n + 3, then what is its order?

--------------------------------------------------------------------
13. Intuition First
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Dominating term is n.

So order should be O(n).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
14. Formal Proof
--------------------------------------------------------------------
2n + 3 ‚â§ c ¬∑ n

Choose:
c = 3

Then:
2n + 3 ‚â§ 3n
3 ‚â§ n

True for n ‚â• 3.

Hence:
f(n) = O(n)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
15. Important Logical Conclusion
--------------------------------------------------------------------
If f(n) = O(n),
then f(n) is ALSO:
- O(n¬≤)
- O(n¬≥)
- O(n‚Å¥)
- ...

Because:
n ‚â§ n¬≤ ‚â§ n¬≥ ‚â§ ...

Big-O gives an UPPER BOUND.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
16. Very Important Concept
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Big-O does NOT represent a single function.
It represents a SET of functions.

Example:
O(n) includes:
- n
- 2n
- n/10
- n + 100
- 1000n + 50

--------------------------------------------------------------------
17. Question 4 (Logarithmic Functions)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Q. Compare log n and n.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
18. Understanding Using Values
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Take log base 2.

n = 2   ‚Üí log n = 1
n = 4   ‚Üí log n = 2
n = 8   ‚Üí log n = 3
n = 16  ‚Üí log n = 4
n = 1024 ‚Üí log n = 10

But n grows as:
2, 4, 8, 16, 1024

--------------------------------------------------------------------
19. Growth Comparison
--------------------------------------------------------------------
If input size doubles:
- log n increases by 1
- n doubles

So n grows MUCH faster than log n.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
20. Big-O Relation
--------------------------------------------------------------------
log n ‚â§ c ¬∑ n

Choose:
c = 1
n‚ÇÄ = 1

Hence:
log n = O(n)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
21. Very Important Generalization
--------------------------------------------------------------------
All functions that are:
- less than
- or equal to
- c ¬∑ n

belong to O(n).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
22. Examples Included in O(n)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
- log n
- log log n
- 5 log n + 6 log log n
- 100000 log n

All are O(n).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
23. Order n¬≤ and Higher Orders
--------------------------------------------------------------------
If order is O(n¬≤),
then all of these belong:
- n¬≤
- n log n
- n
- log n
- constants

But NOT:
- n¬≥
- n‚Å¥

Because higher power grows faster.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
24. Growth Rate Analogy (Teacher‚Äôs Analogy)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Think of:
- n¬≤ as a fast vehicle
- n¬≥ as a rocket

Initially, difference may be small,
but eventually the faster one overtakes.

Higher growth ALWAYS wins in the long run.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
25. Final Conclusions of Big-O
--------------------------------------------------------------------
- Big-O gives an upper bound
- Constants do not matter
- Lower-order terms do not matter
- Big-O represents a SET of functions
- Analysis is done for very large n
- Machine speed is irrelevant

--------------------------------------------------------------------
26. One-Line Definition
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Big-O notation represents the set of functions
whose growth rate is less than or equal to
a given function for sufficiently large n.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
27. What Comes Next
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Next lecture:
- Big-Omega (Œ©)
- Lower bound analysis

